v0.52.3 SMOLT-AGE VERIFICATION RUN
====================================
Date: 2026-04-29
Probe: scripts/_probe_v046_tornionjoki_cohort.py --years 5

[v0.53.0 update — same date]
The "mort_fish_high_temp_T*" hypothesis below was FALSIFIED by a
per-source mortality breakdown probe later the same day. high-temp
daily survival is 1.000000 in EVERY month of the simulation —
T1=28°C/T9=24°C is fully inert at Tornionjoki summer water temps
(12-15°C). The actual dominant kernel killer is mort_terr_pred_*,
which had ~99% daily summer survival = 2.6% annualized (3-7× too
aggressive). v0.53.0 ships the per-source diagnostic primitive
(numpy_backend.survival_with_breakdown) and a targeted Tornionjoki
terr_pred_min raise (0.96-0.97 → 0.99) that lifts annualized
survival to ~23-30% (within real 30-50% range). See
scripts/_v053_breakdown_1yr.log for the falsifying probe data.
[end v0.53.0 update]

Sim: example_tornionjoki, seed=42 (matches test_latitudinal_smolt_age_gradient)
Window: 2011-04-01 → 2016-03-30 (5 years; same as the xfail'd test)
Walltime: ~75 minutes (single Python process, micromamba shiny env)
Source: /tmp/v053_smolt_probe.log (preserved here as durable diagnostic)

VERDICT: v0.52.2 fix delivers natal cohorts but exposes a 6th layer.
  - Modal smolt age STILL 2 (test_latitudinal_smolt_age_gradient still red)
  - All 86 outmigrants are initial-population fish (seeded at 12-20 cm)
  - NO natal cohort produces a smolt over the 5-year window

BUT delivery layer (v0.52.0/v0.52.1/v0.52.2) is GREEN:
  - 2.6M cumulative eggs deposited
  - 11,443 PARR peak (Sept 2012); 11,350/11,274/11,186 in subsequent years
  - eggs_scour_cum stays at 0 across all 5 years (defense_area + EPSG:3035 fixes hold)

LAYER 6 SIGNAL (juvenile in-river survival):
  Sept 2012 → Mar 2013: 11,443 PARR → 2,107 PARR (winter, 18% survival)
  Mar 2013  → Sept 2013:  2,107 PARR →     6 PARR (summer,  0.3% survival)
  Real Tornionjoki Atlantic salmon parr survival is ~30-50% per year.
  Python over-mortality ratio: ~600× (summer is the dominant kill).

LIKELY ROOT CAUSE (hypothesis, deferred to v0.53.x):
  mort_fish_high_temp_T* params were calibrated against the original
  Atmata-baseline warm-river fixture; subarctic Tornionjoki summer
  temps drive what the param table thinks is "lethal hot water".
  Same shape as the lo_T problem v0.52.2 fixed for eggs, on the
  opposite end of the temperature axis.

